[{"id":"/sicpy/5.1.2","tag":"TITLE","body":"5.1.2  \n    Abstraction in Machine Design"},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p1","child":[{"body":"\n    We will often define a machine to include \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"primitive","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\"\n    operations that are actually very complex.  For example, in\n    sections ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.4","href":"/sicpy/5.4"},{"body":" and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.5","href":"/sicpy/5.5"},{"body":"\n    we will treat\n    Python's\n    environment manipulations as primitive.  Such abstraction is valuable\n    because it allows us to ignore the details of parts of a machine so that we\n    can concentrate on other aspects of the design.  The fact that we have\n    swept a lot of complexity under the rug, however, does not mean that a\n    machine design is unrealistic.  We can always replace the complex\n    \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"primitives","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" by simpler primitive operations.\n  ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"TEXT","id":"#p2","child":[{"body":"\n    Consider the GCD machine. The machine has an instruction that computes\n    the remainder of the contents of registers ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"a"},{"body":"\n    and ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"b"},{"body":" and assigns the result to register\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"t"},{"body":".  If we want to construct the GCD machine\n    without using a primitive remainder operation, we must specify how to\n    compute remainders in terms of simpler operations, such as subtraction.\n    Indeed, we can write a \n    Python function\n    that finds remainders in this way:\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":1,"eval":true,"prependLength":0,"program":"chap=4&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniArAOgIzIEwCgsBMCmAZiAE74C2AhgJYB2BJAFLQDQi4CUAXFiH6fgAuAVxK0Q46sXEAediHwAbAM74BVOg2YgAtOzaccABxJ1BjMhvr4mGAJxtEHDkA","body":"def remainder(n, d):\n    return n if n < d else remainder(n - d, d) "},{"body":"\n\n    We can thus replace the remainder operation in the GCD machine's\n    data paths with a subtraction operation and a comparison test.\n    Figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.5","href":"/sicpy/5.1.2#fig-5.5"},{"body":" shows the data paths and\n    controller for the elaborated machine. The instruction\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FIGURE","scale":"30%","src":"img_original/Fig5.5b.std.svg","id":"#fig-5.5","captionHref":"/sicpy/5.1.2#fig-5.5","captionName":"Figure 5.5 ","captionBody":[{"body":"\n\tData paths and controller for the elaborated GCD  machine.\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":2,"eval":false,"body":"assign(\"t\", llist(op(\"rem\"), reg(\"a\"), reg(\"b\")))"},{"body":"\n    in the GCD controller definition is replaced by a sequence of\n    instructions that contains a loop, as shown in\n    figure ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"5.6","href":"/sicpy/5.1.2#fig-5.6"},{"body":".\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"FIGURE","snippet":{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":false,"id":3,"eval":true,"prependLength":404,"program":"chap=4&prgrm=MQAgygkgwgCgniArAOgIzIEwCgsBMCmAZiAMYD2AdgC4BOZANvfjQBQDO+AjgK74Un4AlAC4sIcSBr4q3GhRCMAlmyosAROWp1GzNQBoQHHnwGC8RUpVoMmNAPpHe-fC03WdNEWIlSZckAAW+ACGuCxUwYr0rlbatoJm5sQA5tJ2UsnKVMwsALbBJAGKFPgGGXYUwblCohKS0rLy+YXFLmqpVOn4mSq6gizlldWJBMRUcAAOLsUqNNwkVIqUXnW+jYEhYTO084vLOKMKZGQA1twTdhM0irnscLkARgwGZFM0wXsUbCsSAG7B9BAAF4QME2GwyCQ7o9niBXswPksvmZVg1-CxmHRWGpuBQThQyAB3eTw96fEAAWgpoPB+EeTH0hnuT3oghAimIyjsuNGrTC-1Z3jqwpA+HoHA2oXCkWiAoSIws9GOZwu9GCDzFLDVGvFBm1YoqVRqQpAAuBNIhUP19EN1T16rF3xNa3RmLI2J5RD5CgdgKpFrpDwZ9p1tqE7M5bG5FF5JX5AJRIuFjvwIAiURYcoVxHyJ3wl2uuUUi1++fwAA8LkQMZWDM0iiUQ46fuIOeyo5oVMFqHYKxMaxMW8KSObOxEe327ALeAPEyKXfI1Y9cMFhKQTWK21zrb3K7PakntmxzUrTuc7Natb62E2bZPL32EibUX5F1UHiu10eN-Qt1GMlkzC7v2j4HvO5odF0PTZKw9atGU3SAfYk4ZLOc7CguPrLquICQW4fBUGwAzoSmYHJjQWLqLi+JEvIfZSOCSJppMqb+mCHD0vgjKPgcFi5vmpKIpQwG9oQA51gUDalD6Oo3nCbxCciZGvCeyrnlcNwsIJnwia8s4vApnxOnUwSELix4gvk-Z